Three ways to use it:

Mode 1 — Single window (30 rows exactly)
python predict_csi.py --mode single --file my_30_frames.csv
Output shows the room grid with the predicted block highlighted, confidence, and per-class probability bars:
  Room grid:
  ┌─────────┬─────────┬─────────┐
  │  Block 1│  Block 2│  Block 3│
  ├─────────┼─────────┼─────────┤
  │  Block 4│ ▓▓▓B5▓▓▓│  Block 6│
  ├─────────┼─────────┼─────────┤
  │  Block 7│  Block 8│  Block 9│
  └─────────┴─────────┴─────────┘


Mode 2 — Full file with accuracy report
bash# With ground-truth labels (first column = label)
python predict_csi.py --mode file --file data.csv

# Without labels (pure IQ data, 256 values per row)
python predict_csi.py --mode file --file data.csv --no-labels

# Quiet mode — summary only, no per-window lines
python predict_csi.py --mode file --file data.csv --quiet

# Custom stride (default 1 = every possible window)
python predict_csi.py --mode file --file data.csv --stride 5


Mode 3 — Live buffer (import into your own code)
For real-time use where you feed packets as they arrive:

```
pythonfrom predict_csi import LivePredictor

predictor = LivePredictor(stride=5)   # predict every 5 new frames

for packet in your_csi_stream:
    result = predictor.push(packet)   # None until 30 frames buffered
    if result:
        print(result['class_name'], f"{result['confidence']:.1%}")
        print("Grid pos:", result['coord_grid'])  # e.g. [1.0, 0.5]

# Call predictor.reset() between measurement sessions
```

The preprocessing chain in predict_csi.py is byte-for-byte identical to training: amplitude extraction → empty-ref subtraction → 2-channel stack → same scaler transform → same input shape (1, 30, 128, 2).